  M5 (notes) additionally cross-referenced scripts/artifacts/notes.py — which is
  itself modified from Yogesh Khatri's mac_apt Notes plugin
  (https://github.com/ydkhatri/mac_apt, MIT) — for the notes query column choices
  (a note's ZTITLE1 title, ZSNIPPET, ZCREATIONDATE3 creation date, ZACCOUNT7
  account, ZFOLDER → folder ZTITLE2), the gzip (zlib window 15+32) + protobuf note
  body encoding, and the Media/<identifier>/<generation>/<filename> attachment
  path convention. iLEAPP's OWN note-body decoder (get_uncompressed_data +
  process_note_body_blob) is ported verbatim into deploy/diff_notes.py as the
  independent differential oracle (attributed inline there). Note iLEAPP's notes.py
  returns zero rows on the iOS 17/18 schema (it hard-codes the account join on
  ZACCOUNT4, which moved to ZACCOUNT7), so its full export is not usable as a
  phase-1 oracle; the ported decoder, the store's own SQL, and Apple's stored
  ZSNIPPET are the oracles instead. Attributed inline in notes/schema.go and
  deploy/diff_notes.py.

  M7 (safari) additionally cross-referenced scripts/artifacts/safariBookmarks.py and
  scripts/artifacts/safariHistory.py for the Safari interpretations: the bookmarks
  read (SELECT title, url, hidden FROM bookmarks — every row of the tree), the
  browsing-history history_visits LEFT JOIN history_items join topology, the
  history_visits.origin mapping (0 Local Device / 1 iCloud Synced Device), the
  redirect_source / redirect_destination visit-id → URL resolution, and the
  history_visits.visit_time Cocoa conversion (datetime(visit_time + 978307200,
  'unixepoch')) — which pinned History.db's Cocoa-2001 epoch against Bookmarks.db's
  Unix-1970 last_modified (the two-epoch trap). Attributed inline in safari/types.go
  and deploy/diff_safari.py. iLEAPP is also the differential oracle for safari (its
  Safari Bookmarks and History exports in phase 1; its query semantics re-run in
  phase 2, keyed by bookmarks.id and history_visits.id).

typedstream format (M3 internal/typedstream)
--------------------------------------------

  The typedstream (streamtyped NSArchiver) decoder was implemented FROM PUBLIC
  FORMAT DOCUMENTATION ONLY, per the charter's license hygiene:

  - Chris Sardegna (ReagentX), "Reverse Engineering Apple's typedstream Format" —
    a prose write-up (the imessage-exporter author's published reverse-engineering
    notes; facts about a file format are not copyrightable).
  - dgelessus/python-typedstream (LGPL-3.0-or-later) — its DOCSTRINGS were
    consulted for format facts (notably the two-table shared-reference model: a
    separate shared-string table and shared-object table, each numbered from
    0x92). Function bodies were NOT read and NO code was ported; only the
    documented format facts were used.
  - The file(1) magic database (header bytes) and archived NeXT/GNUstep NSArchiver
    notes.

  python-typedstream is ALSO the independent decoder used as the differential
  oracle for the messages typedstream text (via iLEAPP's sms.py, and directly in
  deploy/diff_messages.py phase 2) — a from-scratch Go decoder validated against a
  different implementation.

imessage-exporter (GPL) and crabstep (its Rust typedstream deserializer) are used
ONLY as black-box differential oracles — executed and compared against, never read
or ported (see the diff-study-messages Makefile target for the documented manual
cross-check). No GPL-licensed code is incorporated into this repository.

Apple Notes body format (M5 internal/applenotes)
------------------------------------------------

  The Apple Notes note-body decoder (gzip of a "Note Store proto") was implemented
  FROM PUBLIC FORMAT DOCUMENTATION ONLY:

  - Published "Apple Notes" reverse-engineering write-ups (CCL Solutions Group /
    Alex Caithness; Ciofeca Forensics) describing the Note Store protobuf — prose
    facts about a file format, not copyrightable.
  - The protobuf wire-format specification (Google's public encoding docs) — the
    universal varint / length-delimited framing the reader walks.
  - The field numbers on the note-text path (document = 2, note = 3, note_text = 2)
    as used by the MIT iLEAPP notes.py, independently confirmed against instrumented
    dumps of the study backup.

  The decoder is a from-scratch recursive-descent protobuf reader; it was validated
  differentially against iLEAPP's own independent (fixed-offset byte-walk) decoder,
  ported into deploy/diff_notes.py (see above). apple_cloud_notes_parser
  (threeplanetssoftware) is used ONLY as an optional black-box manual cross-check
  (see the diff-study-notes Makefile target); its source is not read or ported.
